sources.text: p. 9. Children of Joseph Reeves and Elenor his wife: Mark Reeves was born the 28th of the 12th mo 1723; John Reeves was born the 5th of the 1 mo 1730
sources.citation: Greenwich Monthly Meeting, Record of Births and deaths, 1677-1806, via Ancestry.com, June 15, 2021

sources.text: Mark Reeve, son of Joseph Reeve of the Township of Fairfield in the County of Cumberland in New Jersey, and Hannah Foster, daughter of William Foster of the Township of Evesham and county of Burlington, were married the 22th day of the 10th month 1761.
sources.citation: Evesham Monthly Meeting First Book of Marriages, via Ancestry.com search, June 15, 2021

sources.text: p. 222-225. The Testimony of Greenwich Monthly Meeting concerning our friend Mark Reeve deceased; visited families; was a "zealous advocate" for the "liberation" of "enslaved... Africans"; traveled much in North America in his ministerial capacity; died on the 25th day of the 10th month 1788 ... in the 65th year of his age.
sources.citation: Philadelphia Yearly Meeting book of testimonies (C5.22), via Ancestry.com search, June 15, 2021

resource.title: John Hunt papers, 1770-1828.
resource.abstract: John Hunt kept a diary for more than 40 years, recording Quaker concerns and daily events. This collections consists primarily of the manuscript journal, 1770-1800; fragments of 1805, 1806 & 1808; and 1814-1824. Of particular interest are the visits of prominent Quakers, including Elias Hicks and Jonathan Evans. There is also an account book, some correspondence received, and other miscellaneous materials. Correspondents include Ann R. Matlack, Asa Matlack, Elizabeth A. Lippincott, John Cox, Joseph Foulke, and Josiah Roberts.
